It takes two arguments: `headers`, the list of header-column strings for the
table, and `cells`, the list of already-split/trimmed cell strings for a single
data row. It must return a map that keys each header string to its corresponding
cell value, matched by position: the first header maps to the first cell, the
second header to the second cell, and so on.

The row may be ragged relative to the headers. If `cells` has **fewer** entries
than `headers`, the missing trailing columns are filled with `""`. If `cells`
has **more** entries than `headers`, the extra cells are dropped (there is no
header to key them under). The resulting map therefore always has exactly one
entry per header. Order the work by iterating the headers together with their
index and looking up the cell at that index, defaulting to `""` when absent.

